english:
  title: Miscellaneous Verses on the South
  author: Shin Hyung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A traveler's sorrow and spring's melancholy—both endless, boundless.
    When we meet, we fear only that the wine cup runs dry.
    On this ancient land of a thousand years, the moon stirs the heart to sadness,
    While a single flute in the high tower fills the face with wind.

    Spring enters the halls of poetry, leaving behind vigorous lines,
    And wine charges the siege of sorrow, achieving wonders.
    Who can I ask about the drifting clouds of days gone by?
    All the rises and falls of ages are whispered forth in song.
  footnotes:
    - The poem juxtaposes personal emotion with historical reflection, suggesting that individual sorrow mirrors the transience of kingdoms and empires.
    - The flute and the wind are classical symbols for poetry and the transmission of culture across time.
